


git init: creates new git repo in current directory

git status: shows current state of workspace (staged and unstaged files)
git commit: commits changes to local repo
git log: shows history of commits (across branches)
git rm: removes file (automatically stages deletion I think)
git restore: restores file and stages it


git pull: pulls any changes that have occurred in the remote repo (performs git fetch and git merge together)
git push: pushes local repo to remote repo

git fetch: retrieves commits from online branches as parallel branches (for local merging)

git remote -v: displays connected remote repo
git remote remove origin: disconnect from online repo
git clone [link_to_online_repo]: makes local copy of specified online repo in current directory (retains connection to online repo)
git remote add origin [link_to_online_repo]: connect to specified remote repo

Branching

git branch [branch_name]: creates new branch
git switch [branch_name]: switches to branch
git checkout [branch_name]: switches to branch, can also restore older file versions
git branch -v: displays branches with their most recent commits, indicating current branch
git branch --all: displays all branches (including online repo branches)
git merge [branch_name]: merges changes in [branch_name] to current branch
git branch -d [branch_name]: deletes branch

git branch origin [branch_name]: pushes local branch to new branch in online repo
git branch -u origin [branch_name]: pushes (changes) to online branch [branch_name]
git diff: displays merge conflicts




General notes (defaults etc.)

By default, git pull fetches and merges changes from the remote branch that your current branch is tracking
Checking out a local branch from a remote-tracking branch automatically creates what is called a “tracking branch” (and the branch it tracks is called an “upstream branch”). Tracking branches are local branches that have a direct relationship to a remote branch. If you’re on a tracking branch and type git pull, Git automatically knows which server to fetch from and which branch to merge in.

Good practice

-Seems to be general practice to make python package, install it locally (making it editable if desired so updates are carried forward), then host it on github via commits and push.
-Use different (online) branches for different workflows
-Try to avoid multiple people working on the same branch at the same time
-Even with online branches I think one should merge locally, and then push to main (I'm not sure if it's even possible to directly merge online or upstream branches)

